#
# lutra is a **minimal Secure-Shell manager** in Pony
# — manages SSH hosts (nodes) with optional username,
# port, and key per host.  Pivots from R297 plwm
# (Prolog `library(optparse)`) into the **Pony
# language tooling cluster** — corpus's first
# documented Pony CLI.  Sister tools: corral (Pony
# package manager, ALREADY in corpus from unrelated
# Microsoft Boogie lineage at boogie-org/corral;
# different tool, same name collision), ponyc (Pony
# compiler, ALREADY in corpus as `_pony`).  **MAJOR
# MILESTONE**: corpus's **first documented Pony CLI**
# — adds Pony stdlib `cli` package to the cross-
# language CLI taxonomy (37 library variants now).
#
# Critical extraction note: lutra uses **Pony stdlib
# `cli` package** at lutra/cli.pony:1 — `use "cli"`
# imports the package bundled with every ponyc
# installation (lives at `packages/cli/` in the ponyc
# source tree).  No third-party dependency.  Documents
# the **stdlib-only Pony CLI pattern** — Pony, unlike
# Common Lisp (R291/R295) and Erlang (R292), has a
# CANONICAL STDLIB CLI package.  Distinct from Julia
# (R296 Comonicon — third-party), Prolog (R297
# library(optparse) — stdlib), Pharo (R294 Clap —
# third-party port of Rust clap).  Pony's `cli`
# package is a FIRST-CLASS LANGUAGE FEATURE:
# `CommandSpec`, `OptionSpec`, `ArgSpec`,
# `CommandParser`, `Command`, `CommandHelp`,
# `SyntaxError` are all exposed types.  Corpus's
# **first documented Pony stdlib-CLI**.
#
# Critical extraction note: lutra uses **Pony PARTIAL
# (`?`) annotation for error propagation** at lutra/
# cli.pony:23/52 — `fun _spec(): CommandSpec ? => ...`
# declares the function as PARTIAL (can raise an
# error), and the spec-build expression ends with
# `)?` to propagate any error from `CommandSpec.leaf
# (...)`.  At line 52, `?.>add_help("help", "...")?`
# uses BOTH the partial-call annotation `?` AND the
# CHAINED-MUTATION operator `.>` (calls `add_help`
# on the result, returns the receiver).  Documents
# the **partial-call-with-chained-mutation
# pattern** — UNIQUE to Pony.  Pony's `?` is
# CHECKED at compile time; the caller MUST handle
# the partial via `try ... end` (line 7) or
# propagate further with their own `?`.  Distinct
# from R295 CL clingon `make-option` (no error
# annotation), R296 Julia `@main` (handles errors
# at runtime), and R294 Pharo cascade (no partial
# annotation).  Corpus's **first documented
# Pony-partial-with-mutation CLI pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: lutra uses **Pony
# UNION TYPE return for parse result** at lutra/
# cli.pony:5/12-15 — `parse(...) : (Command | (U8,
# String))` returns EITHER a parsed Command OR a
# tuple `(U8, String)` (exit code + error message).
# Inside, the match expression has THREE arms:
# `Command` (success), `CommandHelp` (user
# requested help), `SyntaxError` (parse failure).
# Documents the **typed-union-return-with-three-
# arm-match pattern** — distinct from R292 Erlang
# `getopt:parse` `{ok, {Opts, _Args}}` / `{error,
# {Reason, Data}}` (tagged-tuple result), R293 Tcl
# `cmdline::getoptions` `array set params`
# (mutating + try/trap), and R296 Julia (return is
# the function's return; errors are exceptions).
# Pony's approach uses STATIC UNION TYPES + COMPILE-
# TIME EXHAUSTIVENESS CHECKING — the match must
# cover all union members or the compiler rejects.
# Corpus's **first documented union-type CLI parse
# result with compile-checked exhaustive match**.
#
# Critical extraction note: lutra uses **Pony
# CHARACTER LITERAL `'p' 'i' 'k' 'l' 'a' 'd' 'u'
# 'f' 's'` for short flags** at lutra/cli.pony:29-
# 45 — `OptionSpec.string("port", "...", 'p',
# "22")` passes `'p'` as the SHORT flag.  In Pony,
# `'p'` is a CHARACTER LITERAL of type `U8` (8-bit
# unsigned integer = ASCII code).  Plus Pony uses
# SINGLE QUOTES for character literals, DOUBLE
# QUOTES for strings — a clear lexical
# distinction.  Documents the **Pony-char-literal
# CLI short-flag pattern** — sister to R291 CL
# `#\p` (CL char literal), R292 Erlang `$p`
# (Erlang char literal), R295 CL `#\A` (clingon
# CL char literal).  Pony's `'p'` evaluates to the
# integer 112 (ASCII 'p'), same as Erlang's `$p`.
# FOUR character-literal CLI cluster languages
# now: CL `#\X`, Erlang `$X`, Pony `'X'`, clingon
# (CL) `#\X`.  Corpus's **fourth character-literal
# CLI flag pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: lutra uses **type-
# method-named factory: `OptionSpec.string`,
# `OptionSpec.bool`, `ArgSpec.string`** at lutra/
# cli.pony:28/30/32/34/36/38/40/42/44/47/49 — the
# TYPE NAME (`string`, `bool`) is the METHOD NAME
# on `OptionSpec` and `ArgSpec`.  Each method
# takes `(name, description, short, default)` for
# OptionSpec or `(name, description, default)` for
# ArgSpec.  Documents the **type-name-as-factory-
# method pattern** — distinct from R295 CL clingon
# `:string`/`:integer`/`:choice` keyword args, R292
# Erlang `string`/`integer`/`boolean` atom tag in
# 5-tuple, and R294 Pharo `(ClapFlag id: #name)`
# class-name discriminator.  Pony's approach: the
# TYPE IS THE METHOD — `OptionSpec.string(...)` is
# a CONSTRUCTOR for string-typed option specs;
# `OptionSpec.bool(...)` for booleans.  Compile-
# time type-safe.  Corpus's **first documented
# type-as-factory-method CLI**.
#
# Critical extraction note: lutra uses **PRIMITIVE
# CLI as namespace** at lutra/cli.pony:3 —
# `primitive CLI fun parse(...) ...` declares
# `CLI` as a PONY PRIMITIVE (a stateless,
# singleton type used as a namespace).  Plus the
# entry-point function lives ON the primitive
# (`CLI.parse(args, envs)` is the call shape).
# Documents the **primitive-as-namespace pattern**
# — unique to Pony.  Pony PRIMITIVES are similar
# to Scala objects or Java static classes but
# more constrained: they have NO FIELDS, NO
# CONSTRUCTOR, and are GLOBALLY UNIQUE.  Distinct
# from R295 CL clingon `(def command ...)`
# (variable binding), R294 Pharo class-side method
# (class as namespace), and R296 Julia `module
# BenchPkg`.  Corpus's **first documented
# primitive-as-CLI-namespace pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: lutra uses **`add_help`
# auto-virtual-subcommand** at lutra/cli.pony:52
# — `)?.>add_help("help", "Get this page.")?`
# AUTOMATICALLY adds a virtual `help` subcommand
# to the spec.  When user types `lutra help`, the
# parser returns a `CommandHelp` (case at line 13),
# which the entry-point converts to exit 0 + help
# text output.  Documents the **library-managed
# virtual-help-subcommand pattern** — convergent
# with R294 Pharo `addHelp` cascade message (also
# library-auto), R295 CL clingon (auto-generates
# --help) and R290 Racket `#:once-each [("-h"
# "--help") ...]` (manual).  Pony's `add_help`
# adds it as a SUBCOMMAND (`lutra help`), not as
# `--help` flag — distinct UX choice.
